To create a JSON file named "userdata.json" with an empty object as its content in the root project directory, you can use the following code snippet:

```java
import java.io.FileWriter;
import java.io.IOException;

public class Settings {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        createUserDataJsonFile();
    }

    private static void createUserDataJsonFile() {
        String fileName = "userdata.json";
        String fileContent = "{}";

        try (FileWriter fileWriter = new FileWriter(fileName)) {
            fileWriter.write(fileContent);
            System.out.println("userdata.json file created successfully.");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("An error occurred while creating the userdata.json file.");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

This code defines a method `createUserDataJsonFile()` that uses a `FileWriter` to write the content (`{}`) to the file named "userdata.json". The file is created in the root project directory. If the file creation is successful, it prints a success message; otherwise, it prints an error message along with the stack trace.

You can call the `createUserDataJsonFile()` method from the `main()` method or any other appropriate place in your code.

To fix the error 'FileWriter' used without 'try'-with-resources statement, you need to use the 'try'-with-resources statement when creating the FileWriter object. This ensures that the FileWriter is automatically closed when it is no longer needed, even if an exception occurs.

Here's an example of how to fix the error:

```java
try (FileWriter fileWriter = new FileWriter("filename.txt")) {
    // Write to the file using the fileWriter object
    fileWriter.write("Hello, World!");
} catch (IOException e) {
    // Handle the exception
    e.printStackTrace();
}
```

In the above code, the FileWriter object is created within the 'try' block, and it is automatically closed at the end of the block. This eliminates the need for an explicit 'close()' call and ensures that the resources are properly released.

Make sure to replace "filename.txt" with the actual file path you want to write to. Additionally, you can add your own code within the 'try' block to perform the necessary file writing operations.

Remember to handle any exceptions that may occur during the file writing process by catching the IOException or any other relevant exceptions.
